### Phase B: Firmware-Aware Agent (The Big Gap)

Embedder's biggest advantage: **the agent IS the firmware agent**. Our Power Mode agent is generic — firmware context is bolted on as a side-band XML block. The agent doesn't know HOW to use registers, WHEN to check serial, or WHY to cross-reference errata.

---

#### [NEW] [firmwareSystemPrompt.ts](file:///Users/sanjaysenthilkumar/Documents/IDE/void/src/vs/workbench/contrib/neuralInverseFirmware/browser/engine/firmwareSystemPrompt.ts)

A firmware-specific system prompt that replaces the generic Power Mode prompt when a firmware session is active. This is the critical differentiator.

```typescript
export function buildFirmwareAgentPrompt(input: {
  mcuConfig: IMCUConfig;
  projectType: FirmwareProjectType;
  peripherals: string[];
  serialConnected: boolean;
  buildSystem: string;
  complianceFrameworks: string[];
  rtos?: string;
}): string
```

The prompt teaches the agent:
1. **Domain reasoning** — "You know when to check a register, when to read serial output, when to check the TRM"
2. **Workflow patterns** — init sequences, clock tree config, peripheral setup checklists
3. **Tool orchestration** — "After writing SPI config code, call fw_get_register_map('SPI1') to verify bit field values"
4. **Safety awareness** — "Always check fw_get_errata before configuring a peripheral"
5. **Build-Flash-Monitor loop** — "After editing code, offer to build. After build succeeds, offer to flash. After flash, monitor serial."

